'', 1999\u20132000\n*''Noises Off'', 2000\u201301\n*''His Dark Materials'', 2003\u201304\n*''Dream Me a Winter'', 2006 (part of the [[Old Vic]]'s '24 Hour Plays')\n*''Boeing Boeing'', 2007\n*''The Country Wife'', 2007\u201308\n*''The Clean House'', 2008\n*''Calendar Girls'', 2008\u201309\n*''The Breath of Life'', 2011\n*''Dandy Dick'', 2012\n*''Relative Values'', 2013\u201314\n*''Travels with My Aunt'', 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2016/apr/27/travels-with-my-aunt-review-graham-greene-patricia-hodge-minerva-chichester|work=The Guardian |title=Travels with My Aunt review|date=27 April 2016|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref>\n*''Copenhagen'', 2018\n*''A Day in the Death of Joe Egg'', 2019\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Award\n!Work\n!Result\n|-\n|1981\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Musical|Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Musical]]\n|''The Mitford Girls''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|1987\n|[[British Academy Television Award for Best Actress|BAFTA TV Award for Best Actress]]\n|''[[Hotel du Lac (film)|Hotel du Lac]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|1990\n|Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Musical\n|''Noel and Gertie''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2000\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Olivier Award for Best Supporting Actress]]\n|''Money''\n|{{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0388092|name=Patricia Hodge}}\n\n{{OlivierAward PlayActress SupportingPerformance 1976\u20132000}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hodge, Patricia}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cleethorpes]]\n[[Category:Laurence Olivier Award winners]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Helen's School]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:20th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Best Actress BAFTA Award (television) nominees]]\n", "name_user": "S k wilson", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patricia_Hodge"}
{"title_page": "C\u00e9cile Kyenge", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = C\u00e9cile Kashetu Kyenge\n|image          = Kashetu kyeng cecile.jpg\n|image_size     = 180px\n|caption = Kyenge in 2013\n|office       = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n|constituency = [[North-East Italy (European Parliament constituency)|North-East Italy]]\n|term_start   = 1 July 2014\n|term_end     = 2 July 2019\n|office2         = [[Italian Minister for Integration|Minister for Integration]]\n|term_start2     = 28 April 2013\n|term_end2       = 22 February 2014\n|president2      = [[Giorgio Napolitano]]\n|primeminister2  = [[Enrico Letta]]\n|predecessor2    = [[Andrea Riccardi]]\n|successor2      = Ministry abolished\n|office3        = [[Chamber of Deputies (Italy)|Member of the Chamber of Deputies]]\n|term_start3    = 26 February 2013\n|term_end3      = 18 February 2014\n|constituency3  = [[Emilia-Romagna]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1964|8|28|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Kambove]], [[DR Congo]]\n|otherparty     = \n|party          = [[Democratic Party (Italy)|Democratic Party]]\n|spouse         = Domenico Grispino <small>(1994\u2013present)</small>\n|children       = Giulia<br />Maisha\n|alma_mater     = [[Universit\u00e0 Cattolica del Sacro Cuore]]\n|profession     = Ophthalmologist\n|occupation     = \n|religion       = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n|website        = \n}}\n'''C\u00e9cile Kashetu Kyenge''' ({{IPA-it|se\u02c8sil \u02c8kj\u025b\u014b\u0261e}}; born '''Kashetu Kyenge''', 28 August 1964) is an Italian politician and [[ophthalmologist]]. She was the Minister for Integration in the 2013\u201314 [[Letta Cabinet]]. From 2014 until 2018, she was a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP). Kyenge is of [[DR Congo|Congolese]] descent.\n\nAfter moving to Italy in 1983 at the age of 19, she became a qualified ophthalmologist in [[Modena]], [[Emilia-Romagna]]. She has founded an intercultural Association (DAWA) to promote mutual awareness, integration and cooperation between Italy and Africa, particularly in her country of birth, the Democratic Republic of Congo. She is also the spokesperson of the association \"March First\", which works to promote the rights of [[Immigration|migrants]] in Italy.\n\nIn February 2013 she was elected member of the [[Chamber of Deputies]] for the [[Democratic Party (Italy)|Democratic Party]] in Emilia-Romagna. Two months later she was appointed Minister for Integration in the [[grand coalition]] government formed by [[Enrico Letta]], becoming Italy's first [[Black people|black]] cabinet minister.<ref name=Bacchi2013>{{cite news|last=Bacchi|first=Umberto|title=Italy's First Black Minister Cecile Kyenge Shrugs off Racial Attacks|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/articles/464330/20130503/italy-cecile-kyenge-racism-minister.htm|accessdate=13 June 2013|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=3 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703161631/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/articles/464330/20130503/italy-cecile-kyenge-racism-minister.htm|archive-date=3 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> She supports the introduction of a ''[[Jus soli]]'' law to grant [[citizenship]] to children of immigrants born on Italian soil.\n\n==Biography==\nKyenge was born in Kambove ([[Haut-Katanga District]]) in the Democratic Republic of Congo on 28 August 1964. She arrived in Italy with a student visa in 1983.<ref name=\"www.ilmessaggero.it\">{{cite news|title=C\u00e9cile Kyenge, per la prima volta nel governo un ministro di colore|url= http://www.ilmessaggero.it/primopiano/politica/ccile_kyenge_letta_governo_pd/notizie/273714.shtml|newspaper=[[Il Messaggero]]\n |date=27 April 2013\n |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130429135922/http://www.ilmessaggero.it/primopiano/politica/ccile_kyenge_letta_governo_pd/notizie/273714.shtml\n |archive-date=29 April 2013\n |url-status=dead\n |accessdate=26 February 2019 }}</ref> She has been married since 1994 to an Italian engineer, Domenico Grispino, and has two daughters named Giulia and Maisha.<ref name=\"gazzettadimodena.gelocal.it\">{{cite news|title=Kyenge: Prester\u00f2 la voce a chi non ne ha possibilit\u00e0|url= http://gazzettadimodena.gelocal.it/cronaca/2013/01/10/news/kyenge-prestero-la-voce-a-chi-non-ne-ha-possibilita-1.6328032| newspaper=Gazzetta di Modena|date=10 January 2013|accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref> She lives in [[Castelfranco Emilia]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Scritto da: Guido Del Duca \u2013 sabato 27 aprile 2013 |url=http://www.polisblog.it/post/81309/cecile-kyenge-chi-e-il-ministro-dellintegrazione |title=Cecile Kyenge; Ministro dell'Integrazione. Governo Letta|work=Polis Blog|accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> She has a degree in medicine and surgery from [[Universit\u00e0 Cattolica del Sacro Cuore|the Universit\u00e0 Cattolica del Sacro Cuore]] in [[Rome]].<ref name=faris>{{cite news|last=Faris|first=Stephen|title=In New Job, Italy\u2019s First Black Minister Confronts Culture of Casual Racism|url=http://world.time.com/2013/05/06/italys-first-black-minister/|accessdate=12 June 2013|newspaper=Time|date=6 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"www.ilmessaggero.it\"/> She is a specialist in ophthalmology at [[University of Modena and Reggio Emilia|the University of Modena and Reggio Emilia]].\n\nIn 2002 she founded the Association for Intercultural DAWA (\"dawa\" is a [[Kiswahili]] word meaning \"medicine\"), with the aim of promoting mutual understanding of different cultures and develop processes of awareness, integration and cooperation between Italy and Africa, particularly in the Democratic Republic of Congo where Kyenge focuses mostly her efforts. Since September 2010 she has been the national spokesperson of the Italian association \"March First\" that works to promote the rights of migrants. She collaborates with various organizations and associations in national campaigns on the rights of citizenship. She collaborates with many Italian magazines, including ''Combonifem'' and ''Corriere Immigrazione'', an online newspaper and a weekly journal on the culture of Italy of the present and future.\n\n==Political career==\nIn 2004 Kyenge was elected in a district of the town of [[Modena]] for the [[Democrats of the Left]] and later became the provincial head of the Forum of International Cooperation and Immigration.\n\nOn 7 June 2009 Kyenge was elected provincial councilor in Modena for the [[Democratic Party (Italy)|Democratic Party]] (PD) and joined the committee Welfare and social policies. She is also responsible for immigration policies in [[Emilia-Romagna]] for the Democratic Party.\n\nOn 25 February 2013 Kyenge was elected member of the [[Chamber of Deputies]] for the PD in Emilia-Romagna.<br />\nImmediately after her election to the [[Italian Parliament]], with the support of other signatories ([[Pier Luigi Bersani]], Khalid Chaouki and [[Roberto Speranza]]), she began to promote a plan for a law granting citizenship to children of immigrants born on Italian soil (a so-called ''[[Ius soli]]'' law).\n\n===Minister for Integration, 2013\u201314===\nIn April 2013 Kyenge was appointed Minister for Integration in the [[grand coalition]] government formed by [[Enrico Letta]], becoming Italy's first [[Black people|black]] cabinet minister.<ref name=Bacchi2013/> Her ministerial nomination was repudiated in some circles on cultural and/or racial grounds, being met by [[racist]] insults from individual politicians belonging to the [[Lega Nord|Northern League]] such as [[Roberto Calderoli]], [[vicepresident|VP]] of the [[Italian Senate]], who called her an [[orangutan]],<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/14/italian-senator-roberto-calderoli-cecile-kyenge</ref> in addition to racist campaigns orchestrated by the [[New Force (Italy)|New Force]] party and other [[far-right]] groups.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/politica/2013/04/30/news/kyenge_zul_insulti_razzisti_sui_siti_della_galassia_nazi-57768619 |title=\"Kyenge zul\u00f9\": insulti razzisti sui siti della galassia nazi|newspaper=La Repubblica|date=30 April 2013|language=Italian|accessdate=12 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio24.ilsole24ore.com/notizie/lazanzara/2013-04-30/mario-borghezio-lega-nord-161429.php |title=Mario Borghezio (Lega Nord) a La Zanzara: \"Kyenge? Con le sue idee ci vuole imporre tradizioni tribali\"|newspaper=La Zanzara|language=Italian|date=30 April 2013|accessdate=12 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=adnkronos2013>{{cite news|title=Italy: Northern League councillor sparks row over calls for black minister's rape|url=http://www.adnkronos.com/IGN/Aki/English/Politics/Italy-Northern-League-councillor-sparks-row-over-calls-for-black-ministers-rape_32293644545.html|accessdate=14 June 2013|work=[[Adnkronos]]|date=13 June 2013}}</ref> Her treatment as Italy's first black minister has been described by ''[[The Economist]]'' as \"shameful\" with \"limited condemnation\".<ref>https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21584376-italys-first-black-minister-has-had-tough-political-baptism-educating-c-cile Racism in Italy: Educating C\u00e9cile</ref> Writer and University of Tokyo Professor Flavio Rizzo further analysed the climate around Minister Kyenge in the context of Italian inability to relate to diversity and \"the emergence of institutional racism\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.warscapes.com/opinion/minister-kyenge-meets-good-italians|title=Minister Kyenge Meets the Good Italians|date=31 July 2013|work=Warscapes|access-date=17 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Member of the European Parliament, 2014\u20132019===\nKyenge was elected to the [[European Parliament]] in the [[2014 European Parliament election in Italy|elections of 2014]] as a candidate for the [[Democratic Party (Italy)|Democratic Party]] from the constituency of [[North-East Italy (European Parliament constituency)|North-East Italy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kyenge elected to the European Parliament|url=http://www.africa-news.eu/immigration-news/italy/6119-kyenge-elected-to-the-european-parliament.html|website=Africa News|access-date=10 November 2014|archive-url=https://archive.is/20141110175403/http://www.africa-news.eu/immigration-news/italy/6119-kyenge-elected-to-the-european-parliament.html|archive-date=10 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=MEP Kashetu Kyenge|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/124801/KASHETU_KYENGE_history.html|publisher=The official website of the European Parliament}}</ref> During her time in parliament, she was a member of the [[Committee on Civil Liberties, Justice and Home Affairs]]. In addition to her committee assignments, she served as vice-chairwoman of the parliament's delegation to the [[ACP\u2013EU Joint Parliamentary Assembly]]. She was also a member of the European Parliament Intergroup on Integrity (Transparency, Anti-Corruption and Organized Crime),<ref>[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/pdf/intergroupes/VIII_LEG_13_Integrity_20151112.pdf Members of the European Parliament on Integrity (Transparency, Anti-Corruption and Organized Crime)] [[European Parliament]].</ref> the European Parliament Intergroup on Extreme Poverty and Human Rights<ref>[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/pdf/intergroupes/VIII_LEG_10_Extreme_poverty_and_human_rights.pdf Members] European Parliament Intergroup on Extreme Poverty and Human Rights.</ref> and the [[European Parliament Intergroup on LGBT Rights]].<ref>[http://www.lgbt-ep.eu/about/members/ Members] European Parliament Intergroup on LGBTI Rights.</ref>\n\nKyenge led the EU-Election Observer Mission for the [[2015 Burkinab\u00e9 general election|2015 general election]] in [[Burkina Faso]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Italy|Democratic Republic of the Congo|Biography|Politics}}\n*[http://www.camera.it/leg17/29?shadow_deputato=305827&idpersona=305827&idlegislatura=17 Profile on the Italian parliament's website] {{in lang|it}}\n* {{MEP}}\n\n{{Letta Cabinet|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kyenge, Cecile}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Haut-Katanga Province]]\n[[Category:People from Castelfranco Emilia]]\n[[Category:Universit\u00e0 Cattolica del Sacro Cuore alumni]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (Italy) politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo emigrants to Italy]]\n[[Category:Democrats of the Left politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies (Italy)]]\n[[Category:Italian ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:Women ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:University of Modena and Reggio Emilia faculty]]\n[[Category:Italian people of Democratic Republic of the Congo descent]]\n[[Category:Letta Cabinet]]\n[[Category:MEPs for Italy 2014\u20132019]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian politicians]]\n[[Category:Women MEPs for Italy]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian physicians]]\n[[Category:Italian women physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Italy]]\n[[Category:20th-century women physicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = C\u00e9cile Kashetu Kyenge\n|image          = Kashetu kyeng cecile.jpg\n|image_size     = 180px\n|caption = Kyenge in 2013\n|office       = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n|constituency = [[North-East Italy (European Parliament constituency)|North-East Italy]]\n|term_start   = 1 July 2014\n|term_end     = 2 July 2019\n|office2         = [[Italian Minister for Integration|Minister for Integration]]\n|term_start2     = 28 April 2013\n|term_end2       = 22 February 2014\n|president2      = [[Giorgio Napolitano]]\n|primeminister2  = [[Enrico Letta]]\n|predecessor2    = [[Andrea Riccardi]]\n|successor2      = Ministry abolished\n|office3        = [[Chamber of Deputies (Italy)|Member of the Chamber of Deputies]]\n|term_start3    = 26 February 2013\n|term_end3      = 18 February 2014\n|constituency3  = [[Emilia-Romagna]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1964|8|28|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Kambove]], [[DR Congo]]\n|otherparty     = \n|party          = [[Democratic Party (Italy)|Democratic Party]]\n|spouse         = Domenico Grispino <small>(1994\u2013present)</small>\n|children       = Giulia<br />Maisha\n|alma_mater     = [[Universit\u00e0 Cattolica del Sacro Cuore]]\n|profession     = Ophthalmologist\n|occupation     = \n|religion       = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n|website        = \n}}\n'''C\u00e9cile Kashetu Kyenge''' ({{IPA-it|se\u02c8sil \u02c8kj\u025b\u014b\u0261e}}; born '''Kashetu Kyenge''', 28 August 1964) is an Italian politician and [[ophthalmologist]]. She was the Minister for Integration in the 2013\u201314 [[Letta Cabinet]]. From 2014 until 2018, she was a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP). Kyenge is of [[DR Congo|Congolese]] descent.\n\nAfter moving to Italy in 1983 at the age of 19, she became a qualified ophthalmologist in [[Modena]], [[Emilia-Romagna]]. She has founded an intercultural Association (DAWA) to promote mutual awareness, integration and cooperation between Italy and Africa, particularly in her country of birth, the Democratic Republic of Congo. She is also the spokesperson of the association \"March First\", which works to promote the rights of [[Immigration|migrants]] in Italy.\n\nIn February 2013 she was elected member of the [[Chamber of Deputies]] for the [[Democratic Party (Italy)|Democratic Party]] in Emilia-Romagna. Two months later she was appointed Minister for Integration in the [[grand coalition]] government formed by [[Enrico Letta]], becoming Italy's first [[Black people|black]] cabinet minister.<ref name=Bacchi2013>{{cite news|last=Bacchi|first=Umberto|title=Italy's First Black Minister Cecile Kyenge Shrugs off Racial Attacks|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/articles/464330/20130503/italy-cecile-kyenge-racism-minister.htm|accessdate=13 June 2013|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=3 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703161631/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/articles/464330/20130503/italy-cecile-kyenge-racism-minister.htm|archive-date=3 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> She supports the introduction of a ''[[Jus soli]]'' law to grant [[citizenship]] to children of immigrants born on Italian soil.\n\n==Biography==\nKyenge was born in Kambove ([[Haut-Katanga District]]) in the Democratic Republic of Congo on 28 August 1964. She arrived in Italy with a student visa in 1983.<ref name=\"www.ilmessaggero.it\">{{cite news|title=C\u00e9cile Kyenge, per la prima volta nel governo un ministro di colore|url= http://www.ilmessaggero.it/primopiano/politica/ccile_kyenge_letta_governo_pd/notizie/273714.shtml|newspaper=[[Il Messaggero]]\n |date=27 April 2013\n |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130429135922/http://www.ilmessaggero.it/primopiano/politica/ccile_kyenge_letta_governo_pd/notizie/273714.shtml\n |archive-date=29 April 2013\n |url-status=dead\n |accessdate=26 February 2019 }}</ref> She has been married since 1994 to an Italian engineer, Domenico Grispino, and has two daughters named Giulia and Maisha.<ref name=\"gazzettadimodena.gelocal.it\">{{cite news|title=Kyenge: Prester\u00f2 la voce a chi non ne ha possibilit\u00e0|url= http://gazzettadimodena.gelocal.it/cronaca/2013/01/10/news/kyenge-prestero-la-voce-a-chi-non-ne-ha-possibilita-1.6328032| newspaper=Gazzetta di Modena|date=10 January 2013|accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref> She lives in [[Castelfranco Emilia]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Scritto da: Guido Del Duca \u2013 sabato 27 aprile 2013 |url=http://www.polisblog.it/post/81309/cecile-kyenge-chi-e-il-ministro-dellintegrazione |title=Cecile Kyenge; Ministro dell'Integrazione. Governo Letta|work=Polis Blog|accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> She has a degree in medicine and surgery from [[Universit\u00e0 Cattolica del Sacro Cuore|the Universit\u00e0 Cattolica del Sacro Cuore]] in [[Rome]].<ref name=faris>{{cite news|last=Faris|first=Stephen|title=In New Job, Italy\u2019s First Black Minister Confronts Culture of Casual Racism|url=http://world.time.com/2013/05/06/italys-first-black-minister/|accessdate=12 June 2013|newspaper=Time|date=6 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"www.ilmessaggero.it\"/> She is a specialist in ophthalmology at [[University of Modena and Reggio Emilia|the University of Modena and Reggio Emilia]].\n\nIn 2002 she founded the Association for Intercultural DAWA (\"dawa\" is a [[Kiswahili]] word meaning \"medicine\"), with the aim of promoting mutual understanding of different cultures and develop processes of awareness, integration and cooperation between Italy and Africa, particularly in the Democratic Republic of Congo where Kyenge focuses mostly her efforts. Since September 2010 she has been the national spokesperson of the Italian association \"March First\" that works to promote the rights of migrants. She collaborates with various organizations and associations in national campaigns on the rights of citizenship. She collaborates with many Italian magazines, including ''Combonifem'' and ''Corriere Immigrazione'', an online newspaper and a weekly journal on the culture of Italy of the present and future.\n\n==Political career==\nIn 2004 Kyenge was elected in a district of the town of [[Modena]] for the [[Democrats of the Left]] and later became the provincial head of the Forum of International Cooperation and Immigration.\n\nOn 7 June 2009 Kyenge was elected provincial councilor in Modena for the [[Democratic Party (Italy)|Democratic Party]] (PD) and joined the committee Welfare and social policies. She is also responsible for immigration policies in [[Emilia-Romagna]] for the Democratic Party.\n\nOn 25 February 2013 Kyenge was elected member of the [[Chamber of Deputies]] for the PD in Emilia-Romagna.<br />\nImmediately after her election to the [[Italian Parliament]], with the support of other signatories ([[Pier Luigi Bersani]], [[Khalid Chaouki]] and [[Roberto Speranza]]), she began to promote a plan for a law granting citizenship to children of immigrants born on Italian soil (a so-called ''[[Ius soli]]'' law).\n\n===Minister for Integration, 2013\u201314===\nIn April 2013 Kyenge was appointed Minister for Integration in the [[grand coalition]] government formed by [[Enrico Letta]], becoming Italy's first [[Black people|black]] cabinet minister.<ref name=Bacchi2013/> Her ministerial nomination was repudiated in some circles on cultural and/or racial grounds, being met by [[racist]] insults from individual politicians belonging to the [[Lega Nord|Northern League]] such as [[Roberto Calderoli]], [[vicepresident|VP]] of the [[Italian Senate]], who called her an [[orangutan]],<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/14/italian-senator-roberto-calderoli-cecile-kyenge</ref> in addition to racist campaigns orchestrated by the [[New Force (Italy)|New Force]] party and other [[far-right]] groups.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/politica/2013/04/30/news/kyenge_zul_insulti_razzisti_sui_siti_della_galassia_nazi-57768619 |title=\"Kyenge zul\u00f9\": insulti razzisti sui siti della galassia nazi|newspaper=La Repubblica|date=30 April 2013|language=Italian|accessdate=12 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio24.ilsole24ore.com/notizie/lazanzara/2013-04-30/mario-borghezio-lega-nord-161429.php |title=Mario Borghezio (Lega Nord) a La Zanzara: \"Kyenge? Con le sue idee ci vuole imporre tradizioni tribali\"|newspaper=La Zanzara|language=Italian|date=30 April 2013|accessdate=12 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=adnkronos2013>{{cite news|title=Italy: Northern League councillor sparks row over calls for black minister's rape|url=http://www.adnkronos.com/IGN/Aki/English/Politics/Italy-Northern-League-councillor-sparks-row-over-calls-for-black-ministers-rape_32293644545.html|accessdate=14 June 2013|work=[[Adnkronos]]|date=13 June 2013}}</ref> Her treatment as Italy's first black minister has been described by ''[[The Economist]]'' as \"shameful\" with \"limited condemnation\".<ref>https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21584376-italys-first-black-minister-has-had-tough-political-baptism-educating-c-cile Racism in Italy: Educating C\u00e9cile</ref> Writer and University of Tokyo Professor Flavio Rizzo further analysed the climate around Minister Kyenge in the context of Italian inability to relate to diversity and \"the emergence of institutional racism\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.warscapes.com/opinion/minister-kyenge-meets-good-italians|title=Minister Kyenge Meets the Good Italians|date=31 July 2013|work=Warscapes|access-date=17 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Member of the European Parliament, 2014\u20132019===\nKyenge was elected to the [[European Parliament]] in the [[2014 European Parliament election in Italy|elections of 2014]] as a candidate for the [[Democratic Party (Italy)|Democratic Party]] from the constituency of [[North-East Italy (European Parliament constituency)|North-East Italy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kyenge elected to the European Parliament|url=http://www.africa-news.eu/immigration-news/italy/6119-kyenge-elected-to-the-european-parliament.html|website=Africa News|access-date=10 November 2014|archive-url=https://archive.is/20141110175403/http://www.africa-news.eu/immigration-news/italy/6119-kyenge-elected-to-the-european-parliament.html|archive-date=10 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=MEP Kashetu Kyenge|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/124801/KASHETU_KYENGE_history.html|publisher=The official website of the European Parliament}}</ref> During her time in parliament, she was a member of the [[Committee on Civil Liberties, Justice and Home Affairs]]. In addition to her committee assignments, she served as vice-chairwoman of the parliament's delegation to the [[ACP\u2013EU Joint Parliamentary Assembly]]. She was also a member of the European Parliament Intergroup on Integrity (Transparency, Anti-Corruption and Organized Crime),<ref>[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/pdf/intergroupes/VIII_LEG_13_Integrity_20151112.pdf Members of the European Parliament on Integrity (Transparency, Anti-Corruption and Organized Crime)] [[European Parliament]].</ref> the European Parliament Intergroup on Extreme Poverty and Human Rights<ref>[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/pdf/intergroupes/VIII_LEG_10_Extreme_poverty_and_human_rights.pdf Members] European Parliament Intergroup on Extreme Poverty and Human Rights.</ref> and the [[European Parliament Intergroup on LGBT Rights]].<ref>[http://www.lgbt-ep.eu/about/members/ Members] European Parliament Intergroup on LGBTI Rights.</ref>\n\nKyenge led the EU-Election Observer Mission for the [[2015 Burkinab\u00e9 general election|2015 general election]] in [[Burkina Faso]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Italy|Democratic Republic of the Congo|Biography|Politics}}\n*[http://www.camera.it/leg17/29?shadow_deputato=305827&idpersona=305827&idlegislatura=17 Profile on the Italian parliament's website] {{in lang|it}}\n* {{MEP}}\n\n{{Letta Cabinet|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kyenge, Cecile}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Haut-Katanga Province]]\n[[Category:People from Castelfranco Emilia]]\n[[Category:Universit\u00e0 Cattolica del Sacro Cuore alumni]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (Italy) politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo emigrants to Italy]]\n[[Category:Democrats of the Left politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies (Italy)]]\n[[Category:Italian ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:Women ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:University of Modena and Reggio Emilia faculty]]\n[[Category:Italian people of Democratic Republic of the Congo descent]]\n[[Category:Letta Cabinet]]\n[[Category:MEPs for Italy 2014\u20132019]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian politicians]]\n[[Category:Women MEPs for Italy]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian physicians]]\n[[Category:Italian women physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Italy]]\n[[Category:20th-century women physicians]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "7-year-old redlink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%C3%A9cile_Kyenge"}
